const result = await architect({
  task: `Review the fix for Task #26 (unreadable white-on-white text in the audit module).

Context: All 28 /audit/* pages were built for a DARK theme (text-white, text-slate-100/200/300, bg-slate-800/900). The app now renders on a LIGHT surface under a parent '.platform-ui' wrapper (from the dashboard layout). globals.css has a comprehensive dark->light conversion block '.audit-light' (lines ~717-830) that converts dark bg/text classes to readable dark-on-light AND preserves white text on colored buttons/badges. The bug was that '.audit-light' was never applied — the audit layout wrapped content in 'bg-slate-950 text-slate-200' instead.

My fix: changed frontend/src/app/(dashboard)/audit/layout.tsx to wrap content in 'audit-light -m-6 min-h-full !bg-[var(--color-subtle)]' (the '!' forces the subtle-gray canvas to win over '.audit-light { background:#fff }' which would otherwise win on source order). Admin and ComplyChat were intentionally left unchanged because they are light-built and only use text-white on colored buttons (already correct).

Evaluate: (1) Is applying '.audit-light' at the audit layout the correct, complete fix? (2) Are there cascade/specificity pitfalls (platform-ui :where rules vs audit-light vs global unscoped .text-white)? (3) Did I correctly scope out admin/ComplyChat, or is there a real risk they're also broken? (4) Any audit edge cases this misses (e.g. inline modals, slate-950, dark classes audit-light doesn't list like bg-slate-800/40, text-slate-50)?`,
  relevantFiles: [
    "frontend/src/app/(dashboard)/audit/layout.tsx",
    "frontend/src/app/(dashboard)/layout.tsx",
    "frontend/src/app/globals.css",
    "frontend/styles/tokens.css",
  ],
  responsibility: "evaluate_task",
  includeGitDiff: true,
});
